 fascism; and the physical and cultural development of most of the important art museums in Europe and the United States, whose prestige depended on their creation of collections of classical art. Accompanied by a discussion of the history of each of the major national traditions and their significant figures, this lively book shows how classical archaeology has influenced attitudes about areas as wide-ranging as tourism, nationalism, the role of the museum, and historicism in nineteenth- and twentieth-century art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAntiquités gréco-romaines. 0aArchaeology and historyxMediterranean Region. 0aArchaeology and historyzMediterranean Region. 0aArchaeologyxHistoryx19th century. 0aArchaeologyxHistoryx20th century. 0aArchaeologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aArchaeologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aArchéologie et histoirexMéditerranée, Région de la. 0aArchéologiexHistoirex19e siècle. 0aArchéologiexHistoirex20e siècle. 0aClassical antiquities. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300134971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300134971.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles